  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What should I do to get selected in GSOC 2018?",
  "response": "To increase your chances of being selected for Google Summer of Code (GSoC) 2018, you would need to focus on several key areas:\n\n1. **Understand GSoC**: GSoC is a program that pairs students with open-source organizations to work on a programming project during the summer. Familiarize yourself with the program details, timeline, and expectations laid out by Google.\n\n2. **Choose the Right Organization**: Start by exploring the list of participating organizations. Find projects that align with your interests and skills. Look into the organization's mission, the size of their community, and the type of projects they work on.\n\n3. **Contribute Early**: Before the application process begins, contribute to the chosen organization\u2019s projects. This can include bug fixes, documentation, or small features. Being an active contributor demonstrates your commitment and helps you get familiar with the codebase.\n\n4. **Connect with the Community**: Join the organization\u2019s communication channels such as mailing lists, chat rooms, or forums. Engage with the community to understand their needs and culture, and don\u2019t hesitate to ask questions.\n\n5. **Select a Project**: Organizations usually provide a list of suggested project ideas. Find a project that matches your skills and interests, but also consider proposing your own project if you see a need.\n\n6. **Prepare a Strong Proposal**: Draft a detailed proposal for your project. Clearly outline your understanding of the project, your approach, expected timelines, and milestones. Highlight your relevant experience and how you plan to overcome potential challenges.\n\n7. **Seek Feedback**: Share your proposal draft with the organization's mentors or community for feedback. Use their advice to refine your proposal before the final submission.\n\n8. **Highlight Your Skills**: Make sure to demonstrate your technical ability and show examples of your previous work, such as contributions to open source, personal projects, or relevant coursework.\n\n9. **Manage Deadlines**: Be aware of all the deadlines, from the application period to proposal submission. Submit your proposal on time and ensure that all necessary information is included.\n\n10. **Be Persistent**: If you aren\u2019t accepted, don\u2019t be discouraged. Seek feedback on your application, continue contributing to open-source, and consider reapplying next year.\n\nNote that this advice is specific to GSoC 2018, and certain aspects of the application process may have changed in subsequent years. Always refer to the latest materials provided by Google and the participating organizations for the most accurate information.",
